{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\n\nProject \"invariants\" = deterministic pattern-rule criteria (banned APIs, layering, naming). The\nconsumer already exists: `code_review/detectors.py` calls the shared `grounding.engine_b.scan` +\n`load_registry` (which already unions `.rebar/detectors/`) + `apply_failclosed`. But it is\nhardcoded to the `rebar.builtin.security.` prefix + 2 criterion mappings and is fail-CLOSED. This\nstory generalizes it into a data-driven, per-criterion-`fail_mode` consumer usable by any project\ninvariant, in both gates.\n\n## What\n\n- Generalize the detector‚Üícriterion mapping: a data-driven `criterion‚Üîdetector` map (drop the\n  hardcoded `rebar.builtin.security.` prefix) so arbitrary `.rebar/detectors/` rules route to an\n  activated DET criterion.\n- Per-criterion `fail_mode: open|closed` on the routing record (default `open` for project\n  invariants; `closed` for the built-in security class). The ORACLE stays fail-open (abstain on\n  absent-binary/parse-error/timeout); the CONSUMER applies `fail_mode` ‚Äî `open` ‚Üí skip=PASS,\n  `closed` ‚Üí BLOCK (the existing `apply_failclosed` path). One code path parameterized by\n  `fail_mode`, not two behaviors.\n- DET fallback descriptor shape (a `_descriptor_from_prompt` DET branch that skips `get_prompt`):\n  `name`=routing name/id, `scenario`=detector rule `message`, `facet`=routing facet (default id),\n  `checklist`=empty. Expand-contract (prompt-backed callers unaffected).\n- Expose the generalized consumer to **plan-review** (which calls no scan consumer today ‚Äî only\n  `refute_absence` in `det_floor.py`); matches are gate-scoped (code-review: diff; plan-review:\n  plan/N-A).\n\n## Scope\n\n- Files: `src/rebar/llm/code_review/detectors.py` (generalize), `src/rebar/llm/plan_review/`\n  (new DET-invariant consumer wiring), `src/rebar/llm/plan_review/registry.py` (DET descriptor\n  branch + `fail_mode`), the routing schema.\n- Depends on story `#1` (registry/overlay/activation). Reuses the shared grounding facade\n  (already unions `.rebar/detectors/`) ‚Äî no new oracle work.\n- Out: graph-level invariants (transitive layering/cycles) ‚Äî a later follow-on, not a new DSL.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] The scan consumer is data-driven (no hardcoded `rebar.builtin.security.` prefix); an\n      activated project DET invariant routes its `.rebar/detectors/` rule and surfaces findings.\n- [ ] Per-criterion `fail_mode` honored: project invariants default fail-open (abstain‚Üískip=PASS);\n      the security class stays fail-closed (abstain‚ÜíBLOCK) via the existing `apply_failclosed`.\n- [ ] DET criteria build a descriptor without a prompt (the DET `_descriptor_from_prompt` branch).\n- [ ] The generalized consumer is wired into plan-review as well as code-review; matches are\n      gate-scoped (diff for code-review; plan/N-A for plan-review).\n- [ ] Fail-open is preserved on engine-binary-absent / parse-error / timeout for `fail_mode:open`.\n\n\n## Plan-review consumer integration (remediation, run 1)\n\n### Match-scoping without a diff (clears G6 blocker 1)\nPlan-review has no diff, so a project DET invariant is scoped to the ticket's DECLARED intent +\nits `file_impact` paths (from the ticket state), NOT a whole-repo scan surfaced as new work:\n- If the ticket declares `file_impact` paths, the consumer scopes matches to THOSE paths (the\n  files this plan intends to touch) ‚Äî the plan-time analog of code-review's `changed_files`\n  diff-scope. A match in a declared file surfaces as a finding.\n- If there is no `file_impact`, the DET invariant is advisory-only over the repo context (it\n  cannot pin the match to this plan's change), never a hard block on a pre-existing whole-repo\n  violation ‚Äî this is why NO baseline/grandfathering is needed (pre-existing violations outside\n  the plan's declared files are not surfaced as new work).\n- An invariant that INHERENTLY needs a diff (e.g. \"no new call to X\") is **N/A at plan time\n  (fail-open)** and belongs to code-review. So plan-time DET scoping ‚àà {file_impact-scoped,\n  advisory-repo-context, N-A-fail-open} ‚Äî never an unscoped whole-repo block.\n\n### Integration point (clears G6 blocker 2)\nThe generalized consumer runs as an ADDITIONAL DET check appended into `det_floor.run_det_floor`\n(alongside P1‚ÄìP9), returning `DetResult`-shaped results (`id=<project criterion id>`, `name=<detector\nrule message>`, `status`, `blocking`, `finding`, `coverage`). Project-invariant results therefore\nflow UNCHANGED through the existing partition in `workflow_ops.plan_review_precheck`\n(`det_blocking_findings` / `det_advisory_findings` / `det_coverage`) ‚Üí `orchestrator.partition_findings`.\nBlocking is gated by the criterion's `fail_mode` + posture: a `fail_mode:open` invariant that abstains\n(engine binary absent / parse-error / timeout) ‚Üí skip=PASS (advisory at most); a `fail_mode:closed`\n(security class) abstain ‚Üí BLOCK (the existing `apply_failclosed` path, now parameterized). A `match`\nin a declared file blocks per the criterion's `default_posture`/`blocking_enabled`.\n\n### Data-driven map location (clears the hardcoded-prefix AC)\nThe detector‚Üícriterion association + `fail_mode` move INTO `criteria_routing.json` (both gates): a\nDET criterion's routing entry carries a `detector` selector (id or id-prefix) + `fail_mode:\nopen|closed`. `run_security_detectors` (renamed to the general `run_detectors`, a thin back-compat\nalias kept) reads the routing map instead of the hardcoded `SECURITY_DETECTOR_PREFIX` /\n`_criterion_for`; the security class is just the built-in rows (`fail_mode: closed`) ‚Äî same code\npath, data-driven. `_validate_routing_entry` gains `fail_mode ‚àà {open, closed}` validation.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria (remediation additions)\n\n- [ ] Plan-review DET-invariant matches are scoped to the ticket's `file_impact` (or advisory when\n      absent) ‚Äî never an unscoped whole-repo block; a test asserts the scoping.\n- [ ] The consumer wires in as a `DetResult`-shaped check via `run_det_floor`, flowing through the\n      existing det_blocking/det_advisory/det_coverage partition; `fail_mode` gates abstain‚Üíblock.\n\n\n## Static P1‚ÄìP9 + dynamic project-check phase (remediation, run 2)\n\n`DET_CHECKS` (the static `(p1_readiness_shape, ‚Ä¶, p9_file_impact_coverage)` tuple) is UNCHANGED ‚Äî\nthe built-in floor stays a fixed constant (expand-contract). `run_det_floor(ctx)` gains a SECOND,\nadditive phase AFTER the static P1‚ÄìP9 loop: it discovers the activated `exec: DET` PROJECT criteria\nat call time from `ctx.repo_root` (via `registry.effective_criteria(ctx.repo_root)` filtered to\n`exec == \"DET\"` + `project.`-prefixed), and for each runs the generalized scan consumer\n(`engine_b.scan` over the criterion's `detector` selector, matches scoped to the ticket's\n`file_impact`) ‚Üí one `DetResult` per criterion, appended to the SAME result list P1‚ÄìP9 return. A\nrepo with no activated project DET criterion (the common case) adds zero checks ‚áí byte-identical to\ntoday. The phase is fail-open (a raising project check ‚Üí `abstain`, logged, per the existing\n`run_det_floor` fail-open contract), so a misbehaving project rule never breaks the floor.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria (remediation additions, run 2)\n\n- [ ] `DET_CHECKS` stays static; `run_det_floor` adds a call-time second phase that discovers\n      activated `exec: DET` project criteria from `ctx.repo_root` and appends their `DetResult`s.\n      A repo with no project DET criterion is byte-identical to today (a test asserts zero added).\n"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1782883268166904001,"uuid":"ceeece56-6363-4eab-89b0-ba2d1b368da7"}